75
00:03:08,020 --> 00:03:10,460
Just from the equation itself.

76
00:03:12,140 --> 00:03:12,700
So,

77
00:03:12,700 --> 00:03:14,280
with Aristotle's equation,

78
00:03:14,280 --> 00:03:17,120
if we know x at an instant,

79
00:03:17,120 --> 00:03:19,120
we also know the velocity.

80
00:03:19,540 --> 00:03:20,020
Now,

81
00:03:20,020 --> 00:03:20,840
what about the acceleration?

82
00:03:20,840 --> 00:03:23,040
Do we know the acceleration?

83
00:03:23,580 --> 00:03:25,980
Let's prove that we can figure out the velocity.

84
00:03:26,000 --> 00:03:26,520
Let's figure out the acceleration.

85
00:03:28,000 --> 00:03:29,500
To figure out the acceleration,

86
00:03:29,500 --> 00:03:31,460
all we have to do is

87
00:03:31,460 --> 00:03:33,420
differentiate this with respect to time.

88
00:03:34,120 --> 00:03:35,540
We'll assume the mass,

89
00:03:35,540 --> 00:03:36,100
in fact,

90
00:03:36,100 --> 00:03:36,980
from here on in,

91
00:03:36,980 --> 00:03:37,660
forever and ever,

92
00:03:37,660 --> 00:03:39,960
mass is a constant.

93
00:03:40,120 --> 00:03:41,420
It doesn't change with time.

94
00:03:41,420 --> 00:03:42,820
The mass of an object,

95
00:03:42,820 --> 00:03:43,780
just to state that.

96
00:03:43,860 --> 00:03:44,360
Of course,

97
00:03:44,360 --> 00:03:45,920
the mass of an object could change.

98
00:03:45,920 --> 00:03:47,580
We could drop the bottom row off this,

99
00:03:47,580 --> 00:03:48,780
and its mass changes.

100
00:03:49,380 --> 00:03:50,990
But that's only because we ignored

101
00:03:50,990 --> 00:03:52,600
part of the system that fell off.

102
00:03:53,660 --> 00:03:54,260
All right,

103
00:03:54,260 --> 00:03:54,880
so here we are.

104
00:03:54,880 --> 00:03:56,820
F equals m dx dt.

105
00:03:57,040 --> 00:03:59,280
Let's differentiate this with respect to time.

106
00:03:59,680 --> 00:04:01,140
Then on the right-hand side,

107
00:04:01,140 --> 00:04:02,600
we'll of course have the acceleration.

108
00:04:03,000 --> 00:04:04,300
Mass times the acceleration.

109
00:04:05,660 --> 00:04:07,180
What about the left-hand side?

110
00:04:07,360 --> 00:04:09,360
The left-hand side will have

111
00:04:09,360 --> 00:04:11,360
the time derivative of the force.

112
00:04:12,100 --> 00:04:14,900
So let's come over to this blackboard

113
00:04:14,900 --> 00:04:17,700
and calculate the time derivative of the force.

114
00:04:18,659 --> 00:04:21,019
Why does the force change in the first place?

115
00:04:21,599 --> 00:04:23,920
It changes because the particle moves.

116
00:04:24,880 --> 00:04:26,800
And depending on where the particle is,

117
00:04:26,800 --> 00:04:28,340
the force will change.

118
00:04:29,020 --> 00:04:33,100
The force only changes because the particle moves.

119
00:04:34,480 --> 00:04:36,160
So let's calculate the time

120
00:04:36,160 --> 00:04:37,840
rate of change of the force.

121
00:04:39,080 --> 00:04:44,920
That's equal to the derivative of the force.

122
00:04:47,680 --> 00:04:49,970
Let's call it the derivative of

123
00:04:49,970 --> 00:04:52,260
the force with respect to position.

124
00:04:53,859 --> 00:04:56,020
I'm using some crazy mixed notation,

125
00:04:56,020 --> 00:04:58,700
partial and the derivative of

126
00:04:58,700 --> 00:05:01,380
the force with respect to position.

127
00:05:01,540 --> 00:05:04,350
That tells you how much the force changes when you

128
00:05:04,350 --> 00:05:07,160
move from one position to another times how fast you move.

129
00:05:08,980 --> 00:05:09,780
dx dt.

130
00:05:10,560 --> 00:05:11,280
In fact,

131
00:05:11,280 --> 00:05:12,140
if you look at this equation,

132
00:05:12,140 --> 00:05:13,610
you'll notice it's correct because

133
00:05:13,610 --> 00:05:15,080
you can cancel out the dx.

134
00:05:15,960 --> 00:05:17,530
The f dt is the

135
00:05:17,530 --> 00:05:19,100
f by dx dx by dt.

136
00:05:19,100 --> 00:05:21,670
And what it tells you is the force

137
00:05:21,670 --> 00:05:24,240
changes with time because it varies with position,

138
00:05:24,240 --> 00:05:27,300
and position is varying with respect to time.

139
00:05:27,620 --> 00:05:30,120
So this then is the

140
00:05:30,120 --> 00:05:32,620
f by dx times the velocity.

141
00:05:33,940 --> 00:05:34,460
Okay,

142
00:05:34,460 --> 00:05:35,400
let's put it in here.

143
00:05:36,760 --> 00:05:41,920
The f by dt is equal to

144
00:05:41,920 --> 00:05:47,080
the f by dx times the velocity.

145
00:05:47,320 --> 00:05:48,720
Let's forget this for a moment.

146
00:05:49,960 --> 00:05:50,480
Well,

147
00:05:50,480 --> 00:05:52,760
that immediately now tells us the acceleration.

148
00:05:53,520 --> 00:05:55,760
We know the force is a function of position.

149
00:05:56,280 --> 00:05:58,390
We can differentiate it and find out

150
00:05:58,390 --> 00:06:00,500
how it varies with respect to position.

151
00:06:00,920 --> 00:06:02,360
So if we know f of x,

152
00:06:02,360 --> 00:06:03,920
we also know df by dx.

153
00:06:04,700 --> 00:06:07,700
And the first equation up here tells us

154
00:06:07,700 --> 00:06:10,700
what the velocity is if we know the position.

155
00:06:11,260 --> 00:06:13,420
If we know the instantaneous position,

156
00:06:13,420 --> 00:06:14,840
we know the velocity.

157
00:06:15,560 --> 00:06:17,080
If we know the velocity,

158
00:06:17,080 --> 00:06:18,800
then we know the acceleration.

159
00:06:20,500 --> 00:06:23,840
So without any further information,

160
00:06:23,840 --> 00:06:25,680
using the equation,

161
00:06:25,680 --> 00:06:29,160
we can also deduce the acceleration of the object.

162
00:06:29,680 --> 00:06:31,000
We can go further.

163
00:06:31,240 --> 00:06:33,620
What's the derivative of acceleration called?

164
00:06:35,980 --> 00:06:36,600
Jerk.

165
00:06:38,740 --> 00:06:39,360
Jerk.

166
00:06:39,850 --> 00:06:41,460
The time derivative of acceleration.

167
00:06:41,740 --> 00:06:42,530
Let's see if we can

168
00:06:42,530 --> 00:06:43,320
work that out just for fun.

169
00:06:43,520 --> 00:06:43,980
Just...

170
00:06:47,180 --> 00:06:48,650
Supposing we differentiate this

171
00:06:48,650 --> 00:06:50,120
equation with respect to time.

172
00:06:50,560 --> 00:06:53,400
Then we'll have m times the jerk,

173
00:06:53,400 --> 00:06:56,280
