00:10:58,680 --> 00:11:02,560
and then the multiple,

287
00:11:02,560 --> 00:11:03,840
all the multiple derivatives.

288
00:11:04,660 --> 00:11:04,940
So,

289
00:11:04,940 --> 00:11:05,680
the lesson is,

290
00:11:05,680 --> 00:11:09,580
in Newton's equations,

291
00:11:09,580 --> 00:11:11,280
which are second order equations,

292
00:11:11,280 --> 00:11:14,240
which involve second derivatives with respect to time,

293
00:11:14,400 --> 00:11:15,860
you need to know,

294
00:11:15,860 --> 00:11:16,740
to get started,

295
00:11:16,740 --> 00:11:18,900
positions and velocities.

296
00:11:19,220 --> 00:11:22,200
You need to know the position and velocity of

297
00:11:22,200 --> 00:11:25,180
every particle and every component of the position and velocity.

298
00:11:26,460 --> 00:11:27,540
If you know that,

299
00:11:27,540 --> 00:11:31,080
then Newton's equations allow you to compute.

300
00:11:31,400 --> 00:11:31,980
And,

301
00:11:31,980 --> 00:11:32,340
of course,

302
00:11:32,340 --> 00:11:34,370
you also need to know the force

303
00:11:34,370 --> 00:11:36,400
law as a function of those positions.

304
00:11:38,480 --> 00:11:40,730
The force law might depend not

305
00:11:40,730 --> 00:11:42,980
only on the position of particles,

306
00:11:43,100 --> 00:11:44,920
but it might depend on the different,

307
00:11:44,920 --> 00:11:47,440
on relative positions and so forth.

308
00:11:48,160 --> 00:11:48,440
But,

309
00:11:48,440 --> 00:11:49,660
if you know all the positions,

310
00:11:49,660 --> 00:11:52,360
then it's assumed that you know the force.

311
00:11:53,140 --> 00:11:55,280
All the positions of all the particles,

312
00:11:55,280 --> 00:11:57,610
then it's assumed that you know the

313
00:11:57,610 --> 00:11:59,940
force on every single one of them,

314
00:12:00,080 --> 00:12:01,420
due to all the others.

315
00:12:02,440 --> 00:12:04,200
That's the assumption of Newton's equations.

316
00:12:05,520 --> 00:12:06,040
Now,

317
00:12:06,040 --> 00:12:08,100
we also talked about conservation of energy.

318
00:12:08,260 --> 00:12:09,660
I think I was getting a little bit tired.

319
00:12:09,800 --> 00:12:11,360
I tend to do that after two hours.

320
00:12:14,340 --> 00:12:14,860
So,

321
00:12:14,860 --> 00:12:16,560
let's just go back quickly

322
00:12:16,560 --> 00:12:18,260
and discuss conservation of energy.

323
00:12:21,800 --> 00:12:23,000
From Newton's equations.

324
00:12:23,280 --> 00:12:24,540
Nothing deep at this point.

325
00:12:24,860 --> 00:12:25,380
I mean,

326
00:12:25,380 --> 00:12:27,130
conservation of energy is clearly

327
00:12:27,130 --> 00:12:28,880
a lot deeper than Newton's equations.

328
00:12:29,720 --> 00:12:32,760
It follows for electromagnetic radiation.

329
00:12:32,760 --> 00:12:35,800
It follows in the theory of electrodynamics.

330
00:12:35,940 --> 00:12:38,060
It works in relativity theory.

331
00:12:38,300 --> 00:12:39,680
It works in general relativity.

332
00:12:40,000 --> 00:12:41,280
It works in quantum mechanics.

333
00:12:41,600 --> 00:12:44,270
There's clearly something much deeper

334
00:12:44,270 --> 00:12:46,940
about the conservation of energy

335
00:12:46,940 --> 00:12:49,280
than just what we're about to demonstrate.

336
00:12:50,060 --> 00:12:50,700
But,

337
00:12:50,700 --> 00:12:51,320
still,

338
00:12:51,320 --> 00:12:52,460
we'll start slow.

339
00:12:53,600 --> 00:12:54,240
Okay.

340
00:12:55,100 --> 00:12:55,740
Now,

