00:34:13,179 --> 00:34:14,600
Now let's add them up.

854
00:34:16,580 --> 00:34:17,699
dP1 by dt,

855
00:34:17,699 --> 00:34:18,920
dP2 by dt,

856
00:34:18,920 --> 00:34:20,239
and dP3 by dt.

857
00:34:20,380 --> 00:34:22,080
That gives us the total

858
00:34:22,080 --> 00:34:23,780
time derivative of the total momentum.

859
00:34:24,560 --> 00:34:25,159
So,

860
00:34:25,159 --> 00:34:27,400
the time derivative of the total momentum,

861
00:34:27,400 --> 00:34:28,440
dP by dt,

862
00:34:29,159 --> 00:34:30,460
is just the sum of

863
00:34:30,460 --> 00:34:31,760
everything in the right hand corner.

864
00:34:31,780 --> 00:34:32,060
The left hand side.

865
00:34:32,400 --> 00:34:33,960
But they cancel in pairs.

866
00:34:34,620 --> 00:34:36,600
F12 is minus F21.

867
00:34:38,020 --> 00:34:39,920
This is just saying the forces cancel.

868
00:34:40,780 --> 00:34:42,940
F13 is minus F31,

869
00:34:42,940 --> 00:34:45,580
and F23 is minus F23.

870
00:34:46,800 --> 00:34:48,400
They all add up to zero.

871
00:34:48,699 --> 00:34:51,249
And it says that the

872
00:34:51,249 --> 00:34:53,800
total momentum of any closed system

873
00:34:53,800 --> 00:34:56,659
means a system with no external forces on it.

874
00:34:57,120 --> 00:34:57,980
Of course,

875
00:34:57,980 --> 00:34:59,420
we might have other forces,

876
00:35:00,060 --> 00:35:02,140
due to some other object in the system.

877
00:35:02,620 --> 00:35:05,240
Then we would have to take it into account also.

878
00:35:06,080 --> 00:35:07,700
But if we have a closed system,

879
00:35:07,760 --> 00:35:09,210
a closed system means we've

880
00:35:09,210 --> 00:35:10,660
accounted for everything in the system

881
00:35:10,660 --> 00:35:11,980
that can exert forces.

882
00:35:12,560 --> 00:35:15,460
Then the time rate of change of momentum is zero,

883
00:35:15,520 --> 00:35:17,480
and momentum is conserved.

884
00:35:20,060 --> 00:35:20,580
Again,

885
00:35:20,580 --> 00:35:22,860
it comes from a rather special assumption

886
00:35:24,720 --> 00:35:26,020
about Newtonian forces,

887
00:35:26,760 --> 00:35:28,640
but it's far more general.

888
00:35:28,640 --> 00:35:30,800
It applies to light.

889
00:35:31,120 --> 00:35:34,160
If a light ray bangs into the wall,

890
00:35:34,460 --> 00:35:36,720
it'll give the wall a little bit of push.

891
00:35:36,880 --> 00:35:38,620
It'll change the momentum of the wall.

892
00:35:38,820 --> 00:35:39,000
Why?

893
00:35:39,000 --> 00:35:40,740
Because the light ray has some momentum.

894
00:35:41,040 --> 00:35:42,860
It applies in quantum mechanics.

895
00:35:43,100 --> 00:35:45,020
It applies in the general theory of relativity.

896
00:35:45,880 --> 00:35:47,080
So it's far,

897
00:35:47,080 --> 00:35:49,880
far more general than this little example shows.

898
00:35:53,880 --> 00:35:58,040
And our object will eventually be

899
00:35:58,040 --> 00:36:00,260
to write the laws of physics,

900
00:36:00,980 --> 00:36:02,120
in particular mechanics,

901
00:36:02,860 --> 00:36:05,100
in a form which is so general

902
00:36:05,100 --> 00:36:08,480
that we can see why these things had to happen.

903
00:36:09,280 --> 00:36:09,880
Okay,

904
00:36:09,880 --> 00:36:12,060
any questions?

905
00:36:14,640 --> 00:36:15,360
Yes?

906
00:36:15,800 --> 00:36:18,100
Is action and reaction instant?

907
00:36:20,000 --> 00:36:20,720
Loud.

908
00:36:20,880 --> 00:36:22,840
Is action and reaction instant?

909
00:36:23,500 --> 00:36:25,200
In Newtonian physics,

910
00:36:25,200 --> 00:36:25,740
it is.

911
00:36:26,440 --> 00:36:27,320
All right?

912
00:36:27,320 --> 00:36:28,520
In classical mechanics,

913
00:36:28,520 --> 00:36:29,580
Newtonian physics,

914
00:36:29,900 --> 00:36:32,940
and Newtonian physics means forget relativity.

915
00:36:34,480 --> 00:36:35,520
In Newtonian,

916
00:36:35,520 --> 00:36:36,800
let's put it this way.

917
00:36:37,200 --> 00:36:38,620
In Newtonian physics,

918
00:36:38,620 --> 00:36:39,900
the speed of light is infinite.

919
00:36:40,240 --> 00:36:42,120
You turn on the lights

920
00:36:42,120 --> 00:36:44,000
and the room lights up instantaneously.

921
00:36:44,280 --> 00:36:45,260
There's no lag.

922
00:36:45,760 --> 00:36:46,920
In the real world,

923
00:36:46,920 --> 00:36:47,320
of course,

924
00:36:48,100 --> 00:36:50,160
forces do not act instantaneously.

925
00:36:50,240 --> 00:36:51,980
It takes time for a force,

926
00:36:52,100 --> 00:36:55,520
when you do something to a particle over here,

927
00:36:55,700 --> 00:36:57,020
it takes time for it to,

928
00:36:57,320 --> 00:36:58,520
for a force to respond over there.

929
00:36:59,300 --> 00:37:00,720
That's because of relativity,

930
00:37:00,720 --> 00:37:02,040
special relativity.

931
00:37:02,320 --> 00:37:05,300
We're assuming Newtonian physics,

932
00:37:06,100 --> 00:37:09,500
and Newtonian physics means that forces are instantaneous.

933
00:37:09,940 --> 00:37:10,660
So yes,

934
00:37:10,660 --> 00:37:11,980
we're assuming they're instantaneous.

935
00:37:12,580 --> 00:37:13,260
Again,

936
00:37:16,460 --> 00:37:19,900
what's curious is that special relativity

937
00:37:21,720 --> 00:37:24,260
undermines that instantaneousness of forces,

938
00:37:24,420 --> 00:37:26,120
but it does not undermine

939
00:37:27,320 --> 00:37:28,340
the conservation of momentum.

940
00:37:29,660 --> 00:37:31,380
So it's somehow much deeper

941
00:37:31,380 --> 00:37:33,980
than our examples indicate.

942
00:37:35,320 --> 00:37:37,840
The momentum law seems a little more deeper

943
00:37:37,840 --> 00:37:38,820
than the energy law,

944
00:37:38,820 --> 00:37:40,260
in the sense that...

945
00:37:40,260 --> 00:37:41,400
It's easier to derive.

946
00:37:42,680 --> 00:37:43,200
Also,

947
00:37:43,200 --> 00:37:44,820
you can choose any direction,

948
00:37:45,820 --> 00:37:46,720
and momentum,

949
00:37:46,720 --> 00:37:48,620
the component of momentum,

950
00:37:48,700 --> 00:37:50,020
will be conserved in that direction.

951
00:37:50,160 --> 00:37:51,820
It seems like there are more laws...

952
00:37:51,820 --> 00:37:52,260
Right,

953
00:37:52,260 --> 00:37:53,320
there are more momentum laws

954
00:37:53,320 --> 00:37:54,240
than there is energy law.

955
00:37:54,980 --> 00:37:56,660
How many momentum laws are there

956
00:37:56,660 --> 00:37:57,600
for a single particle,

957
00:37:57,600 --> 00:37:58,160
for example?

958
00:37:58,340 --> 00:37:58,540
Well,

959
00:37:58,540 --> 00:38:00,320
how many momentum laws are there altogether

960
00:38:00,320 --> 00:38:02,160
for a combined system?

961
00:38:02,500 --> 00:38:02,840
Three.

962
00:38:03,000 --> 00:38:04,340
One for each direction of space.

963
00:38:05,340 --> 00:38:06,640
How many energy laws?

964
00:38:06,860 --> 00:38:07,100
One.

965
00:38:07,480 --> 00:38:08,320
So altogether,

966
00:38:08,320 --> 00:38:09,940
there are four conservation laws.

967
00:38:10,440 --> 00:38:12,760
Three for the three directions of space,

968
00:38:12,900 --> 00:38:14,340
and one for the direction of time.

969
00:38:15,020 --> 00:38:17,060
And in the special theory of relativity,

970
00:38:17,440 --> 00:38:22,220
they form a complex of four related conservation laws,

971
00:38:22,540 --> 00:38:24,340
but this...

972
00:38:24,340 --> 00:38:26,340
It's more general than that.

973
00:38:27,480 --> 00:38:28,040
Okay.

974
00:38:28,760 --> 00:38:29,320
Now,

975
00:38:29,320 --> 00:38:31,840
it's my usual...

976
00:38:32,900 --> 00:38:33,460
Yeah.

977
00:38:34,520 --> 00:38:36,200
We're going to need a little bit of mathematics,

978
00:38:36,640 --> 00:38:37,880
not heavy-duty mathematics,

979
00:38:37,880 --> 00:38:38,860
fairly light,

980
00:38:39,580 --> 00:38:42,100
but let's spend a little bit of time...

981
00:38:42,100 --> 00:38:42,980
What we're going to do next

982
00:38:42,980 --> 00:38:43,860
is we're going to go on

983
00:38:43,860 --> 00:38:48,140
to what really is the deep law of classical physics.

984
00:38:48,380 --> 00:38:51,640
It's called the principle or the law of least action.

985
00:38:52,300 --> 00:38:54,100
And it contains all this junk.

986
00:38:54,640 --> 00:38:56,240
The law of least action,

987
00:38:56,660 --> 00:38:58,180
has all of this stuck into it,

988
00:38:58,180 --> 00:38:58,880
plus a lot more.

989
00:38:59,800 --> 00:39:01,580
But before we do,

990
00:39:01,580 --> 00:39:03,000
we need some math.

991
00:39:03,820 --> 00:39:04,780
Elementary mathematics,

992
00:39:04,780 --> 00:39:05,860
extremely simple.

993
00:39:06,220 --> 00:39:07,720
Math that you know very well.

994
00:39:10,620 --> 00:39:12,120
I just want to spell it out

995
00:39:13,400 --> 00:39:16,260
and remind some of you who haven't done calculus

996
00:39:16,260 --> 00:39:18,360
for a couple of years,

997
00:39:19,420 --> 00:39:23,000
so that we're all on the same playing field.

998
00:39:24,040 --> 00:39:24,520
Okay.

999
00:39:25,740 --> 00:39:28,360
The first thing has to do with minimizing functions.

1000
00:39:29,120 --> 00:39:30,480
This is very elementary.

1001
00:39:30,680 --> 00:39:32,100
I'm not telling you anything you don't know.

1002
00:39:32,280 --> 00:39:34,700
If you have a function of several variables,

1003
00:39:34,920 --> 00:39:36,600
let's start with a function of one variable.

1004
00:39:37,500 --> 00:39:38,200
Function of y.

1005
00:39:41,380 --> 00:39:42,260
Some known...

1006
00:39:42,260 --> 00:39:43,020
Not force.

1007
00:39:43,240 --> 00:39:44,920
F does not stand for force now.

1008
00:39:44,980 --> 00:39:45,760
It just stands for function.

1009
00:39:46,460 --> 00:39:47,180
F of y.

1010
00:39:49,020 --> 00:39:53,040
And y is just some generic independent variable.

1011
00:39:54,140 --> 00:39:54,680
Okay.

1012
00:39:55,180 --> 00:39:55,980
Here it is.

1013
00:39:56,040 --> 00:39:57,060
Here's the function.

1014
00:39:57,200 --> 00:39:57,620
It's plotted.

1015
00:39:57,920 --> 00:39:58,460
Vertically,

1016
00:39:58,460 --> 00:39:59,280
I plot f.

1017
00:40:00,140 --> 00:40:00,680
Horizontally,

1018
00:40:00,680 --> 00:40:02,360
I plot the independent variable y.

1019
00:40:02,760 --> 00:40:04,140
And it has some shape,

1020
00:40:04,140 --> 00:40:04,620
something.

1021
00:40:06,220 --> 00:40:07,520
The first fact is,

1022
00:40:07,520 --> 00:40:09,900
if you want to find the local minima,

1023
00:40:09,900 --> 00:40:12,160
the local minima of the function

1024
00:40:12,930 --> 00:40:14,720
mean the places where,

1025
00:40:14,720 --> 00:40:15,900
if you're there,

1026
00:40:16,180 --> 00:40:18,300
if you go in either direction,

1027
00:40:18,560 --> 00:40:20,140
the function increases.

1028
00:40:21,160 --> 00:40:22,620
A global minimum

1029
00:40:23,040 --> 00:40:24,580
would mean the absolute minimum,

1030
00:40:24,720 --> 00:40:26,120
the lowest possible minimum.

1031
00:40:26,600 --> 00:40:29,100
But we're going to speak about local minima.

1032
00:40:29,100 --> 00:40:30,850
Local minima mean that if

1033
00:40:30,850 --> 00:40:32,600
you are confined to that region,

1034
00:40:32,880 --> 00:40:34,760
you would think that the function

1035
00:40:34,760 --> 00:40:36,640
was minimum right at that point.

1036
00:40:37,840 --> 00:40:41,520
What is the mathematical condition for searching for minima?

1037
00:40:42,600 --> 00:40:43,200
Well...

1038
00:40:44,360 --> 00:40:47,140
The derivative of a function should be equal to zero.

1039
00:40:47,320 --> 00:40:47,680
Right.

1040
00:40:48,400 --> 00:40:50,780
That's not sufficient.

1041
00:40:51,280 --> 00:40:51,540
Yeah.

1042
00:40:53,040 --> 00:40:53,300
Yeah.

1043
00:40:55,400 --> 00:40:56,000
Right.

1044
00:40:56,220 --> 00:40:58,060
So the first condition,

1045
00:40:58,060 --> 00:40:59,300
and the easiest one,

1046
00:41:00,040 --> 00:41:01,780
is that at a minimum,

1047
00:41:02,000 --> 00:41:04,120
the slope of the function is zero.

1048
00:41:06,980 --> 00:41:09,040
That says that the derivative of the

1049
00:41:09,040 --> 00:41:11,100
function is equal to zero at minima.

1050
00:41:11,180 --> 00:41:13,120
It's also zero at maxima,

1051
00:41:13,120 --> 00:41:13,400
notice.

1052
00:41:14,320 --> 00:41:14,920
Right.

1053
00:41:16,120 --> 00:41:18,940
The first condition is that df by dx,

1054
00:41:19,280 --> 00:41:20,360
or df by dy,

1055
00:41:22,700 --> 00:41:23,860
total derivative,

1056
00:41:24,160 --> 00:41:24,920
in this case,

1057
00:41:24,920 --> 00:41:26,560
total derivative,

1058
00:41:26,660 --> 00:41:28,360
if it's only a function of one variable,

1059
00:41:31,360 --> 00:41:32,600
is equal to zero.

1060
00:41:33,520 --> 00:41:34,120
Now,

1061
00:41:34,120 --> 00:41:35,300
there are other conditions.

1062
00:41:35,720 --> 00:41:39,180
The other conditions are basically there to sort out

1063
00:41:39,180 --> 00:41:40,800
two other cases.

1064
00:41:41,260 --> 00:41:42,360
The maximum,

1065
00:41:44,120 --> 00:41:47,380
the f by dy is also zero at maxima,

1066
00:41:48,700 --> 00:41:49,300
but,

1067
00:41:49,300 --> 00:41:51,400
you can check

1068
00:41:52,620 --> 00:41:54,500
whether it's a maximum or a minimum

1069
00:41:54,500 --> 00:41:56,200
by looking at the second derivative.

1070
00:41:56,700 --> 00:41:59,540
The second derivative is positive at a minimum

1071
00:41:59,540 --> 00:42:01,740
and negative at a maximum.

1072
00:42:01,980 --> 00:42:04,220
But we're not going to worry about that distinction.

1073
00:42:05,260 --> 00:42:06,720
The principle of...

1074
00:42:06,720 --> 00:42:08,660
What's the generic term

1075
00:42:09,400 --> 00:42:13,120
for a function which is either maximum or minimum,

1076
00:42:13,260 --> 00:42:14,840
and you may not know which?

1077
00:42:16,200 --> 00:42:16,520
Extremum.

1078
00:42:17,880 --> 00:42:19,120
Extremum is one word.

1079
00:42:19,120 --> 00:42:20,520
In fact,

1080
00:42:20,520 --> 00:42:22,580
there's even another possibility,

1081
00:42:22,940 --> 00:42:25,800
an inflection point where the function is flat

1082
00:42:25,800 --> 00:42:27,280
and then goes down like that.

1083
00:42:27,760 --> 00:42:28,420
Again,

1084
00:42:28,420 --> 00:42:30,060
zero derivative at that point.

1085
00:42:30,680 --> 00:42:34,440
X cubed is a function which has a...

1086
00:42:35,100 --> 00:42:37,760
an inflection point like that at the origin.

1087
00:42:38,500 --> 00:42:41,840
Its derivative is also zero at the origin.

1088
00:42:42,720 --> 00:42:44,880
Knowing that the derivative is zero

1089
00:42:44,880 --> 00:42:47,340
doesn't sort out these three cases of

1090
00:42:47,340 --> 00:42:48,000
minimum,

1091
00:42:48,000 --> 00:42:48,680
maximum,

1092
00:42:49,280 --> 00:42:50,380
or inflection point.

1093
00:42:51,380 --> 00:42:51,900
So,

1094
00:42:52,060 --> 00:42:54,620
the word for either minimum or maximum

1095
00:42:54,620 --> 00:42:56,240
is extremal,

1096
00:42:56,260 --> 00:42:57,240
extremum point,

1097
00:42:57,460 --> 00:42:59,020
but what's the word for

1098
00:42:59,020 --> 00:43:00,660
any one of these three?

1099
00:43:03,320 --> 00:43:03,840
Stationary,

1100
00:43:03,840 --> 00:43:04,260
stationary.

1101
00:43:05,380 --> 00:43:05,900
Stationary.

1102
00:43:05,900 --> 00:43:07,560
The function is stationary at those points.

1103
00:43:08,000 --> 00:43:08,780
Which means

1104
00:43:08,780 --> 00:43:10,680
that if you move a little to the left

1105
00:43:10,680 --> 00:43:11,580
or move it to the right,

1106
00:43:11,760 --> 00:43:13,860
it neither increases nor decreases.

1107
00:43:14,360 --> 00:43:14,840
Well,

1108
00:43:14,840 --> 00:43:15,500
it may increase

1109
00:43:15,500 --> 00:43:17,080
to second order,

1110
00:43:17,080 --> 00:43:18,520
but it doesn't increase to first order.

1111
00:43:18,580 --> 00:43:19,720
The derivative is zero there.

1112
00:43:20,060 --> 00:43:21,400
It's said to be stationary.

1113
00:43:22,080 --> 00:43:24,300
The real principle of least action

1114
00:43:24,300 --> 00:43:26,600
is really the principle of stationary action.

1115
00:43:27,420 --> 00:43:29,480
We'll call it the principle of least action

1116
00:43:29,480 --> 00:43:31,560
and always pretend that we're looking for

1117
00:43:31,560 --> 00:43:32,500
minima of things,

1118
00:43:33,200 --> 00:43:34,640
but in fact,

1119
00:43:34,740 --> 00:43:36,240
it's more general.

1120
00:43:37,140 --> 00:43:39,640
The principle of action

1121
00:43:40,260 --> 00:43:42,260
is the principle of stationary action.

1122
00:43:42,480 --> 00:43:44,020
But I'm not going to draw that distinction

1123
00:43:44,800 --> 00:43:46,120
after this point now.

1124
00:43:47,240 --> 00:43:49,540
The condition for a stationary point

1125
00:43:49,540 --> 00:43:52,560
is that the derivative of f with respect to y

1126
00:43:52,560 --> 00:43:53,320
is equal to zero.

1127
00:43:54,240 --> 00:43:56,560
And I'll often say minimum,

1128
00:43:56,680 --> 00:43:58,760
but I will mean stationary point.

1129
00:43:58,980 --> 00:43:59,460
Now,

1130
00:43:59,460 --> 00:44:00,560
supposing we have a function

1131
00:44:00,560 --> 00:44:02,280
which is a function of several variables,

1132
00:44:03,960 --> 00:44:05,140
f of x and y.

1133
00:44:11,280 --> 00:44:13,100
And let's think about it.

1134
00:44:13,140 --> 00:44:14,560
Let's draw the xy plane.

1135
00:44:17,259 --> 00:44:18,900
At every point on this plane,

1136
00:44:19,020 --> 00:44:20,480
the function takes on some value.

1137
00:44:20,960 --> 00:44:22,500
We could describe the function

1138
00:44:22,500 --> 00:44:23,960
by a sort of contour map.

1139
00:44:27,420 --> 00:44:28,880
You've all seen contour maps.

1140
00:44:29,040 --> 00:44:29,900
You know what they look like.

1141
00:44:33,220 --> 00:44:35,340
Each contour describing

1142
00:44:35,960 --> 00:44:38,040
a particular value of the function.

1143
00:44:38,220 --> 00:44:39,340
And as you move from one point,

1144
00:44:39,460 --> 00:44:41,420
one contour point to another contour point,

1145
00:44:41,520 --> 00:44:42,300
the function changes.

1146
00:44:42,860 --> 00:44:43,300
Well,

1147
00:44:43,300 --> 00:44:43,780
all right,

1148
00:44:43,780 --> 00:44:45,200
I don't need the contour map.

1149
00:44:45,360 --> 00:44:46,100
All we need to do is draw the xy plane.

1150
00:44:46,100 --> 00:44:46,620
All we need to do is to remember

1151
00:44:46,620 --> 00:44:48,240
that the function has some value

1152
00:44:48,240 --> 00:44:51,140
at every point on this two-dimensional plane.

1153
00:44:52,160 --> 00:44:52,760
Now,

1154
00:44:52,760 --> 00:44:53,800
supposing what I want

1155
00:44:54,900 --> 00:44:56,160
is the minimum,

1156
00:44:56,160 --> 00:44:57,340
local minimum,

1157
00:44:57,560 --> 00:44:59,260
with respect to two variables.

1158
00:44:59,819 --> 00:45:01,400
What that means is a point

1159
00:45:02,020 --> 00:45:03,580
where the function is minimum

1160
00:45:03,960 --> 00:45:06,260
no matter what direction you move off in.

1161
00:45:08,780 --> 00:45:10,740
It could be any number of dimensions.

1162
00:45:11,940 --> 00:45:13,260
I'm interested in points

1163
00:45:13,260 --> 00:45:14,460
where the function

1164
00:45:15,400 --> 00:45:16,280
achieves a minimum,

1165
00:45:17,100 --> 00:45:18,920
which means that any direction

1166
00:45:18,920 --> 00:45:19,960
that you move off in,

1167
00:45:20,120 --> 00:45:22,040
the function increases.

1168
00:45:24,320 --> 00:45:25,440
However you move.

1169
00:45:25,680 --> 00:45:28,820
Think of it as the bottom of a bowl.

1170
00:45:29,600 --> 00:45:30,120
Right.

1171
00:45:30,600 --> 00:45:32,520
Are you talking stationary again?

1172
00:45:32,840 --> 00:45:33,360
Yeah,

1173
00:45:33,360 --> 00:45:34,720
strictly speaking,

1174
00:45:34,880 --> 00:45:35,640
we're talking stationary.

1175
00:45:36,080 --> 00:45:38,140
But I'll use the terminology of minimum.

1176
00:45:39,580 --> 00:45:41,300
And if you want to think about it,

1177
00:45:41,320 --> 00:45:42,200
think about minimum.

1178
00:45:42,420 --> 00:45:44,260
You won't be making any serious

1179
00:45:44,460 --> 00:45:45,620
mistakes because in fact,

1180
00:45:45,780 --> 00:45:48,260
almost every case in mechanics,

1181
00:45:48,540 --> 00:45:50,800
we really are talking about

1182
00:45:50,800 --> 00:45:51,680
the minimum action.

1183
00:45:52,060 --> 00:45:52,900
I have a question.

1184
00:45:53,100 --> 00:45:56,220
I think I read that if forces are conservative,

1185
00:45:56,600 --> 00:45:58,900
that it is not a maximum.

1186
00:46:01,480 --> 00:46:03,140
If forces are conservative,

1187
00:46:03,300 --> 00:46:04,240
it's not a maximum,

1188
00:46:04,400 --> 00:46:07,580
but I think that's probably not true

1189
00:46:07,580 --> 00:46:09,400
if there are velocity-dependent forces

1190
00:46:09,400 --> 00:46:10,600
like magnetic forces,

1191
00:46:11,460 --> 00:46:12,840
although I've never checked that.

1192
00:46:13,520 --> 00:46:15,320
That would be the non-perturbative case.

1193
00:46:16,359 --> 00:46:17,240
Non-perturbative?

1194
00:46:18,759 --> 00:46:19,640
Non-conservative.

1195
00:46:19,700 --> 00:46:19,920
No,

1196
00:46:19,920 --> 00:46:20,320
no,

1197
00:46:20,320 --> 00:46:20,500
no,

1198
00:46:20,500 --> 00:46:20,660
no,

1199
00:46:20,660 --> 00:46:20,800
no,

1200
00:46:20,800 --> 00:46:20,900
no.

1201
00:46:21,440 --> 00:46:22,920
Magnetic forces are conservative,

1202
00:46:23,160 --> 00:46:25,000
but they're different in nature than...

1203
00:46:25,440 --> 00:46:26,880
Let's not get into them at the moment.

1204
00:46:27,000 --> 00:46:27,820
We'll come back to them.

1205
00:46:28,700 --> 00:46:31,180
I believe there are cases in physics

1206
00:46:31,180 --> 00:46:33,420
where the action is not minimum,

1207
00:46:33,480 --> 00:46:34,040
but they're unusual.

1208
00:46:34,460 --> 00:46:35,540
So let's just say minimum.

1209
00:46:35,740 --> 00:46:36,180
Minimum,

1210
00:46:36,180 --> 00:46:36,340
minimum.

1211
00:46:36,560 --> 00:46:39,780
Let's not worry about that subtlety.

1212
00:46:40,220 --> 00:46:40,840
All right.

1213
00:46:40,840 --> 00:46:41,660
Well,

1214
00:46:41,660 --> 00:46:42,600
first of all,

1215
00:46:42,600 --> 00:46:45,440
let's suppose we are...

1216
00:46:47,000 --> 00:46:48,340
There's a minimum right there,

1217
00:46:48,500 --> 00:46:50,020
and let's look at the function...

1218
00:46:50,020 --> 00:46:50,740
Whoops,

1219
00:46:50,740 --> 00:46:52,140
I meant to go right through that point.

1220
00:46:53,260 --> 00:46:54,420
Let's look at the function

1221
00:46:54,420 --> 00:46:56,420
as we move to the left or right

1222
00:46:56,420 --> 00:46:57,560
away from that point.

1223
00:46:58,320 --> 00:47:01,160
Now the function is only a function of one variable.

1224
00:47:01,400 --> 00:47:03,300
Think of it as a function of one variable

1225
00:47:03,300 --> 00:47:04,440
along this line.

1226
00:47:05,160 --> 00:47:06,660
It should achieve a minimum

1227
00:47:06,660 --> 00:47:08,120
right at this point.

1228
00:47:08,500 --> 00:47:10,820
So that means as you move along this line,

1229
00:47:13,060 --> 00:47:14,840
ignoring all the other lines,

1230
00:47:15,000 --> 00:47:17,480
the function should be minimum at that point,

1231
00:47:17,620 --> 00:47:20,240
and that says that the derivative of f

1232
00:47:20,240 --> 00:47:21,660
with respect to x

1233
00:47:24,000 --> 00:47:25,260
should be equal to zero.

1234
00:47:26,280 --> 00:47:28,260
But we can say exactly the same thing

1235
00:47:28,260 --> 00:47:29,720
about moving on the vertical axis.

1236
00:47:30,600 --> 00:47:32,960
If the function is minimum at that point,

1237
00:47:33,020 --> 00:47:35,840
it will be minimum with respect to a vertical motion.

1238
00:47:36,400 --> 00:47:38,140
So that says the function...

1239
00:47:41,980 --> 00:47:44,780
should have no derivative with respect to y.

1240
00:47:45,640 --> 00:47:46,900
If you have a function

1241
00:47:46,900 --> 00:47:48,160
of a whole bunch of variables,

1242
00:47:48,980 --> 00:47:52,260
let's give them the generic name x sub i now.

1243
00:47:53,400 --> 00:47:54,860
Function of x sub i.

1244
00:47:57,140 --> 00:48:00,480
The condition that you're at a local minimum

1245
00:48:00,480 --> 00:48:02,780
is that the derivative of f

1246
00:48:02,780 --> 00:48:06,660
with respect to every one of the x sub i's,

1247
00:48:06,820 --> 00:48:09,100
every single one should be equal to zero.

1248
00:48:10,860 --> 00:48:13,440
Let's do an example or two just to...

1249
00:48:17,280 --> 00:48:19,840
I think as a function of one variable,

1250
00:48:19,960 --> 00:48:21,520
we don't need to do an example.

1251
00:48:21,780 --> 00:48:23,620
Let's take a function of two variables

1252
00:48:23,620 --> 00:48:26,440
and find its local minimum.

1253
00:48:27,600 --> 00:48:28,160
Just,

1254
00:48:28,160 --> 00:48:28,940
in fact,

1255
00:48:28,940 --> 00:48:31,220
it will be its global minimum.

1256
00:48:35,720 --> 00:48:38,720
I'm just arbitrarily making up a silly function now.

1257
00:48:41,020 --> 00:48:41,760
All right,

1258
00:48:41,760 --> 00:48:42,200
here it is.

1259
00:48:43,000 --> 00:48:45,020
x squared plus y squared

1260
00:48:46,140 --> 00:48:49,060
plus 3x plus 2y

1261
00:48:53,080 --> 00:48:54,740
let's put in plus xy

1262
00:48:57,540 --> 00:48:58,660
plus 7.

1263
00:48:59,820 --> 00:49:00,780
That's my function.

1264
00:49:01,520 --> 00:49:04,560
I want to find out where that function is minimum.

1265
00:49:05,060 --> 00:49:05,720
All right?

1266
00:49:05,760 --> 00:49:08,100
So I differentiate it with respect to x

1267
00:49:08,100 --> 00:49:09,960
and set the derivative equal to zero.

1268
00:49:10,220 --> 00:49:11,660
That gives me one equation.

1269
00:49:12,680 --> 00:49:14,120
Do the same thing for y.

1270
00:49:14,240 --> 00:49:15,360
It gives me a second equation.

1271
00:49:15,840 --> 00:49:17,140
What are those equations for?

1272
00:49:17,560 --> 00:49:18,800
They're for x and y.

1273
00:49:19,160 --> 00:49:21,120
They tell me where the minimum is achieved.

1274
00:49:21,600 --> 00:49:23,560
So I have two equations for two unknowns.

1275
00:49:24,140 --> 00:49:25,960
Let's work them out just as an example.

1276
00:49:28,880 --> 00:49:29,740
The derivative,

1277
00:49:29,740 --> 00:49:31,500
the partial derivative of f

1278
00:49:31,500 --> 00:49:32,640
with respect to x,

1279
00:49:35,060 --> 00:49:36,000
df by dx.

1280
00:49:40,040 --> 00:49:40,780
All right,

1281
00:49:40,780 --> 00:49:41,900
that's from this term,

1282
00:49:41,900 --> 00:49:42,600
we just get y.

1283
00:49:43,500 --> 00:49:44,500
From this term,

1284
00:49:44,500 --> 00:49:45,580
we get plus 2x.

1285
00:49:46,460 --> 00:49:48,660
This term doesn't depend on x altogether.

1286
00:49:49,680 --> 00:49:50,640
From this term,

1287
00:49:50,640 --> 00:49:51,480
we just get 3.

1288
00:49:52,080 --> 00:49:54,700
And there are no other terms which depend on x.

1289
00:49:55,200 --> 00:49:56,530
So this is the derivative

1290
00:49:56,530 --> 00:49:57,860
of f with respect to x,

1291
00:49:58,500 --> 00:50:00,540
pretending that y were just a constant.

1292
00:50:01,100 --> 00:50:01,760
All right,

1293
00:50:01,760 --> 00:50:02,700
that's the partial derivative.

1294
00:50:03,240 --> 00:50:04,380
And our rule is,

1295
00:50:04,380 --> 00:50:05,500
set this equal to zero.

1296
00:50:06,360 --> 00:50:08,080
That's one equation for x squared.

1297
00:50:08,100 --> 00:50:08,270
And we're going to do the

1298
00:50:08,270 --> 00:50:08,440
same thing for x and y.

1299
00:50:09,060 --> 00:50:09,700
All right,

1300
00:50:09,700 --> 00:50:11,300
let's do the same thing df by dy.

1301
00:50:14,280 --> 00:50:14,960
All right,

1302
00:50:14,960 --> 00:50:19,500
df by dy is x

1303
00:50:19,500 --> 00:50:24,040
plus 2y plus 2 equals zero.

1304
00:50:24,680 --> 00:50:27,460
Here are two linear equations for x and y.

1305
00:50:27,700 --> 00:50:29,140
You can sit down and solve them.

1306
00:50:30,600 --> 00:50:32,960
Notice that the 7 didn't come into it at all.

1307
00:50:33,880 --> 00:50:34,600
Why not?

1308
00:50:35,000 --> 00:50:36,620
Because the 7 is just the height,

1309
00:50:36,620 --> 00:50:37,940
the overall height of the function,

1310
00:50:38,060 --> 00:50:39,640
and it doesn't change where the minimum is.

1311
00:50:40,840 --> 00:50:41,460
All right,

1312
00:50:41,460 --> 00:50:45,920
so I'll tell you what the answer is.

1313
00:50:46,740 --> 00:50:49,820
It's x is equal to minus 8 thirds,

1314
00:50:50,080 --> 00:50:52,800
and y is equal to minus 1 third.

1315
00:50:52,940 --> 00:50:54,000
And if that's not correct,

1316
00:50:54,000 --> 00:50:57,580
it's not important.

1317
00:50:59,260 --> 00:51:00,580
Is it minus 1 third?

1318
00:51:02,620 --> 00:51:04,620
I lost the paper that I did it on.

1319
00:51:05,800 --> 00:51:07,680
But it's not important.

1320
00:51:08,620 --> 00:51:10,520
There is an answer to the problem,

1321
00:51:10,520 --> 00:51:11,140
as you can see.

1322
00:51:11,220 --> 00:51:12,660
It's just two equations for two unknowns.

1323
00:51:13,080 --> 00:51:15,100
If you have n unknowns,

1324
00:51:15,100 --> 00:51:16,180
in other words,

1325
00:51:16,180 --> 00:51:18,300
if you have a function of n variables,

1326
00:51:18,620 --> 00:51:20,700
then there are n equations like this.

1327
00:51:21,040 --> 00:51:24,500
n equations for n unknowns typically will have a solution.

1328
00:51:24,820 --> 00:51:25,520
Not always.

1329
00:51:26,160 --> 00:51:28,000
Some functions don't have minima.

1330
00:51:28,260 --> 00:51:29,180
For example,

1331
00:51:29,180 --> 00:51:31,480
if I took a function that just was like that,

1332
00:51:32,220 --> 00:51:33,120
forever and ever,

1333
00:51:33,120 --> 00:51:34,180
it wouldn't have a minimum.

1334
00:51:34,180 --> 00:51:36,400
There would just be no solution.

1335
00:51:36,700 --> 00:51:38,900
There would be no point at which the derivative vanished.

1336
00:51:40,060 --> 00:51:42,020
Sometimes there's more than one solution.

1337
00:51:42,300 --> 00:51:43,320
For example,

1338
00:51:43,320 --> 00:51:44,540
if I took a function

1339
00:51:44,540 --> 00:51:45,760
with a few minima in it.

1340
00:51:46,140 --> 00:51:49,240
But you have enough equations

1341
00:51:49,240 --> 00:51:52,340
for enough unknowns to locate solutions.

1342
00:51:53,940 --> 00:51:54,720
All right,

1343
00:51:54,720 --> 00:51:58,300
that's mathematical point number one.

1344
00:51:58,500 --> 00:52:01,420
You find stationary points or minima

1345
00:52:02,880 --> 00:52:04,160
by different equations.

1346
00:52:04,180 --> 00:52:05,200
You're differentiating the function.

1347
00:52:05,460 --> 00:52:08,560
Or another way of saying it is finding points

1348
00:52:08,560 --> 00:52:10,740
where if you vary the function a little bit,

1349
00:52:10,920 --> 00:52:11,940
it doesn't change.

1350
00:52:12,500 --> 00:52:15,460
It doesn't change the first order in the variation,

1351
00:52:15,460 --> 00:52:16,340
basically.

1352
00:52:17,420 --> 00:52:18,180
All right,

1353
00:52:18,180 --> 00:52:21,520
so that's the principle of stationary functions.

1354
00:52:22,860 --> 00:52:23,460
Now,

1355
00:52:23,460 --> 00:52:26,460
we're not going to be interested in minimizing functions

1356
00:52:27,060 --> 00:52:29,380
of a finite number of variables.

1357
00:52:29,960 --> 00:52:31,760
We're going to be interested in something

1358
00:52:31,760 --> 00:52:32,100
which,

1359
00:52:32,100 --> 00:52:32,800
at the face of it,

1360
00:52:32,800 --> 00:52:34,460
seems far more complicated.

1361
00:52:35,420 --> 00:52:38,640
It's minimizing expressions which depend

1362
00:52:38,640 --> 00:52:41,520
not on some finite set of variables,

1363
00:52:41,860 --> 00:52:45,120
but which themselves depend on whole functions,

1364
00:52:45,320 --> 00:52:47,160
whole trajectories,

1365
00:52:49,660 --> 00:52:53,380
minimizing quantities which depend on a whole trajectory.

1366
00:52:55,080 --> 00:52:57,760
Before I give you an example,

1367
00:52:58,700 --> 00:53:00,480
let me just say some words about

1368
00:53:00,480 --> 00:53:02,780
what the basic principle of stationary functions is.

1369
00:53:02,800 --> 00:53:04,360
And what the basic problem of mechanics is.

1370
00:53:05,380 --> 00:53:07,040
And more than that,

1371
00:53:07,100 --> 00:53:08,880
the basic problem of classical physics,

1372
00:53:09,120 --> 00:53:09,960
but let's say mechanics.

1373
00:53:10,380 --> 00:53:13,240
The basic problem of mechanics is to determine

1374
00:53:13,799 --> 00:53:15,400
the trajectory of a system

1375
00:53:15,400 --> 00:53:18,640
from its initial starting conditions.

1376
00:53:19,960 --> 00:53:22,900
That's the mathematical problem.

1377
00:53:23,380 --> 00:53:24,000
Now,

1378
00:53:24,000 --> 00:53:24,300
of course,

1379
00:53:24,300 --> 00:53:25,360
in every case,

1380
00:53:25,420 --> 00:53:28,080
we may not really be interested in determining

1381
00:53:29,600 --> 00:53:31,700
if we have 10 to the 23rd particles,

1382
00:53:32,480 --> 00:53:34,520
determining the trajectory of that system

1383
00:53:34,520 --> 00:53:36,520
is equivalent to determining the trajectories

1384
00:53:36,520 --> 00:53:38,260
of all 10 to the 23rd particles.

1385
00:53:38,760 --> 00:53:40,360
Nobody tries to do that.

1386
00:53:40,640 --> 00:53:41,240
Instead,

1387
00:53:41,240 --> 00:53:44,280
we may make some statistical statements about it,

1388
00:53:44,360 --> 00:53:47,560
or some approximate statements.

1389
00:53:48,040 --> 00:53:52,540
But the very precise question of classical mechanics

1390
00:53:52,540 --> 00:53:55,720
is determining the trajectory of a system.

1391
00:53:56,060 --> 00:53:56,660
Now,

1392
00:53:56,660 --> 00:53:57,100
what does it mean?

1393
00:53:57,480 --> 00:53:59,540
We spoke last time a little bit

1394
00:53:59,540 --> 00:54:01,140
about generalized coordinates.

1395
00:54:02,540 --> 00:54:04,960
Generalized coordinates are simply

1396
00:54:04,960 --> 00:54:07,000
the coordinates of a system.

1397
00:54:07,200 --> 00:54:09,140
They could be the Cartesian coordinates

1398
00:54:09,140 --> 00:54:12,420
of the positions of a system of particles.

1399
00:54:12,860 --> 00:54:14,320
They could be angles.

1400
00:54:14,760 --> 00:54:17,640
They could be the orientation of this eraser.

1401
00:54:18,760 --> 00:54:21,400
They could be any number of different kinds

1402
00:54:21,400 --> 00:54:24,260
of coordinates that we might use.

1403
00:54:24,400 --> 00:54:24,860
For example,

1404
00:54:24,860 --> 00:54:26,260
on the surface of the Earth,

1405
00:54:26,380 --> 00:54:28,200
we might use latitude and longitude

1406
00:54:28,200 --> 00:54:29,480
to locate an object.

1407
00:54:30,980 --> 00:54:33,380
Those are all generalized coordinates,

1408
00:54:33,640 --> 00:54:36,620
and they may not be Cartesian coordinates.

1409
00:54:36,740 --> 00:54:39,500
They may be angles or other funny kinds of variables.

1410
00:54:40,220 --> 00:54:44,740
But they do serve to locate an object in space,

1411
00:54:45,000 --> 00:54:48,420
or locate a system in space.

1412
00:54:49,280 --> 00:54:51,800
Those are called the generalized coordinates,

1413
00:54:51,960 --> 00:54:53,880
and they're often labeled by Q.

1414
00:54:55,820 --> 00:54:58,540
Q1 dot dot dot through Qn.

1415
00:55:00,080 --> 00:55:01,920
For a single particle,

1416
00:55:02,160 --> 00:55:03,360
there are three Qs.

1417
00:55:04,160 --> 00:55:04,560
X,

1418
00:55:04,560 --> 00:55:04,860
Y,

1419
00:55:04,860 --> 00:55:05,200
and Z.

1420
00:55:05,580 --> 00:55:06,540
For two particles,

1421
00:55:06,540 --> 00:55:08,060
there are six Qs.

1422
00:55:09,500 --> 00:55:10,300
The X,

1423
00:55:10,300 --> 00:55:10,460
Y,

1424
00:55:10,460 --> 00:55:11,380
and Z of one particle

1425
00:55:11,380 --> 00:55:11,860
and the X,

1426
00:55:11,860 --> 00:55:11,980
Y,

1427
00:55:11,980 --> 00:55:12,980
and Z of the other particle.

1428
00:55:13,920 --> 00:55:15,660
If there are 10 to the 23rd particles,

1429
00:55:16,440 --> 00:55:19,740
there are three times 10 to the 23rd Qs.

1430
00:55:20,640 --> 00:55:22,020
But as we've seen already,

1431
00:55:22,280 --> 00:55:24,600
the Qs are not enough

1432
00:55:25,299 --> 00:55:27,080
to be able to predict the future.

1433
00:55:27,800 --> 00:55:29,320
If you want to predict the future,

1434
00:55:29,480 --> 00:55:30,900
you also need the velocities.

1435
00:55:31,360 --> 00:55:33,720
So in a more general abstract language,

1436
00:55:34,160 --> 00:55:36,620
it also means that you need the Q dots,

1437
00:55:37,319 --> 00:55:38,320
the time derivatives.

1438
00:55:41,400 --> 00:55:44,880
You need six n pieces of information

1439
00:55:45,480 --> 00:55:47,700
for n particles to predict the future.

1440
00:55:48,760 --> 00:55:50,520
Now what does it mean to predict the future?

1441
00:55:50,720 --> 00:55:51,780
It means to determine

1442
00:55:52,400 --> 00:55:54,200
the trajectory of the system,

1443
00:55:54,300 --> 00:55:55,720
which means Q1 of t,

1444
00:55:56,760 --> 00:55:57,820
Q2 of t,

1445
00:56:01,660 --> 00:56:02,600
Q3 of t.

1446
00:56:03,920 --> 00:56:06,660
It means to determine all of the coordinates

1447
00:56:06,660 --> 00:56:08,060
as a function of time.

1448
00:56:10,200 --> 00:56:12,220
All of the particle coordinates

1449
00:56:12,220 --> 00:56:15,520
or the angles or the orientation angles

1450
00:56:15,520 --> 00:56:17,580
or whatever it is to determine all of them,

1451
00:56:17,620 --> 00:56:19,260
not just one of them as a function of time,

1452
00:56:19,380 --> 00:56:20,040
but all of them.

1453
00:56:21,260 --> 00:56:23,400
Such a system of functions

1454
00:56:23,400 --> 00:56:24,700
as a function of time,

1455
00:56:24,840 --> 00:56:27,440
we can call a generalized trajectory.

1456
00:56:27,440 --> 00:56:30,300
A generalized trajectory,

1457
00:56:30,780 --> 00:56:34,100
we can imagine horizontally

1458
00:56:35,240 --> 00:56:37,660
plotting all of the Qs.

1459
00:56:37,800 --> 00:56:38,880
Now horizontally,

1460
00:56:39,100 --> 00:56:40,780
I've just drawn two dimensions here.

1461
00:56:42,140 --> 00:56:44,480
Two dimensions will be a stand-in

1462
00:56:44,480 --> 00:56:48,080
for any number of dimensions,

1463
00:56:48,560 --> 00:56:49,780
Q1 through Qn.

1464
00:56:49,940 --> 00:56:51,120
And vertically,

1465
00:56:51,120 --> 00:56:52,380
we plot the time.

1466
00:56:53,960 --> 00:56:57,060
A trajectory simply means exactly what it says.

1467
00:56:57,060 --> 00:56:58,860
Because a trajectory through the space

1468
00:56:58,860 --> 00:57:01,260
and a trajectory through the space

1469
00:57:01,260 --> 00:57:05,900
is a system of Qs at every value of time.

1470
00:57:06,560 --> 00:57:08,640
That's the mathematical problem

1471
00:57:09,860 --> 00:57:11,520
that's put in front of us

1472
00:57:11,520 --> 00:57:15,100
by the questions of classical mechanics.

1473
00:57:15,600 --> 00:57:18,220
To what extent can we determine

1474
00:57:18,220 --> 00:57:20,100
the trajectory from the starting point?

1475
00:57:20,400 --> 00:57:21,020
All right,

1476
00:57:21,020 --> 00:57:22,160
the answer of course is,

1477
00:57:22,340 --> 00:57:23,360
given Newton's equations,

1478
00:57:23,500 --> 00:57:26,300
we can predict the Q of t,

1479
00:57:26,300 --> 00:57:28,420
not just from the starting point,

1480
00:57:28,600 --> 00:57:30,000
we need the Qs and

1481
00:57:30,000 --> 00:57:31,400
the Q dots to start with.

1482
00:57:31,620 --> 00:57:33,320
If we know the Qs and the Q dots,

1483
00:57:33,580 --> 00:57:35,420
we can determine the trajectory.

1484
00:57:36,680 --> 00:57:38,400
The equations of motion,

1485
00:57:38,660 --> 00:57:40,320
the Newton's equations of motion,

1486
00:57:40,660 --> 00:57:42,360
what they tell us is,

1487
00:57:42,500 --> 00:57:44,660
every point along this trajectory,

1488
00:57:45,080 --> 00:57:46,840
they kind of tell us,

1489
00:57:46,880 --> 00:57:48,460
if we're moving in a certain way,

1490
00:57:48,640 --> 00:57:50,240
how to move next.

1491
00:57:51,060 --> 00:57:52,700
They tell us that if

1492
00:57:52,700 --> 00:57:54,340
we know the velocity along here,

1493
00:57:55,880 --> 00:57:56,660
or sorry,

1494
00:57:56,660 --> 00:57:58,380
if we know where we are along here

1495
00:57:58,380 --> 00:57:59,320
and we know the forces,

1496
00:57:59,620 --> 00:58:01,160
then we know the acceleration.

1497
00:58:01,800 --> 00:58:04,080
So that tells us if we know where we are

1498
00:58:04,080 --> 00:58:05,280
and we know where we're moving,

1499
00:58:05,500 --> 00:58:07,140
we know where we'll be next

1500
00:58:07,140 --> 00:58:08,840
and we know where we'll be moving next.

1501
00:58:10,000 --> 00:58:12,660
The way to say this is that

1502
00:58:12,660 --> 00:58:15,460
Newton's equations are local equations

1503
00:58:15,460 --> 00:58:16,700
along the trajectory,

1504
00:58:17,180 --> 00:58:18,720
and they tell us information,

1505
00:58:18,960 --> 00:58:20,900
they tell us how to proceed from one point

1506
00:58:20,900 --> 00:58:23,280
to the next along the trajectory.

1507
00:58:23,840 --> 00:58:25,240
You don't need to know anything

1508
00:58:25,240 --> 00:58:26,660
about the rest of the trajectory.

1509
00:58:27,220 --> 00:58:28,980
If you know where you are over here,

1510
00:58:29,100 --> 00:58:30,380
and you know which way you're going,

1511
00:58:30,700 --> 00:58:32,320
then you know where you'll be next

1512
00:58:32,320 --> 00:58:33,880
and you know where you'll be going next.

1513
00:58:35,200 --> 00:58:37,140
So they're local equations,

1514
00:58:37,680 --> 00:58:39,780
and that's why they're differential equations.

1515
00:58:40,140 --> 00:58:41,720
Differential equations are equations

1516
00:58:41,720 --> 00:58:44,780
among the positions and the derivatives and so forth,

1517
00:58:44,940 --> 00:58:46,140
and that's the kind of

1518
00:58:46,140 --> 00:58:47,340
information that they have in them.

1519
00:58:47,800 --> 00:58:48,160
Now,

1520
00:58:48,160 --> 00:58:48,520
of course,

1521
00:58:48,520 --> 00:58:49,520
if you know this information

1522
00:58:49,520 --> 00:58:50,940
all along the trajectory,

1523
00:58:50,940 --> 00:58:53,200
then you can build up the whole trajectory.

1524
00:58:53,620 --> 00:58:56,140
But the equation itself is an equation

1525
00:58:56,140 --> 00:58:58,040
which tells you local information.

1526
00:58:59,300 --> 00:59:01,600
The principle of least action

1527
00:59:01,600 --> 00:59:04,640
is another formulation of the same physics

1528
00:59:04,640 --> 00:59:07,340
which looks at the trajectory as a whole.

1529
00:59:08,540 --> 00:59:11,340
Instead of being given the position

1530
00:59:11,340 --> 00:59:14,220
and the velocity at a single time,

1531
00:59:14,680 --> 00:59:17,020
what you're given is different kind of information.

1532
00:59:17,480 --> 00:59:19,120
You're given the position

1533
00:59:19,120 --> 00:59:20,740
at the beginning of a trajectory,

1534
00:59:22,360 --> 00:59:24,660
it could be the position of this eraser

1535
00:59:24,660 --> 00:59:26,140
at time t equals zero,

1536
00:59:27,840 --> 00:59:31,420
and after a certain specified amount of time,

1537
00:59:32,840 --> 00:59:34,680
you're given the position of the system

1538
00:59:34,680 --> 00:59:36,020
at the end of the trajectory.

1539
00:59:36,660 --> 00:59:37,540
In other words,

1540
00:59:37,540 --> 00:59:38,900
you're given the two endpoints

1541
00:59:38,900 --> 00:59:39,700
of the trajectory.

1542
00:59:41,860 --> 00:59:42,340
So,

1543
00:59:42,340 --> 00:59:42,940
for example,

1544
00:59:42,940 --> 00:59:44,060
here's an example,

1545
00:59:44,180 --> 00:59:44,700
here's the eraser.

1546
00:59:45,000 --> 00:59:47,220
I tell you at time t equals zero,

1547
00:59:47,220 --> 00:59:47,980
it's over here.

1548
00:59:49,300 --> 00:59:50,920
I'm not going to tell you how it's moving,

1549
00:59:50,940 --> 00:59:52,090
so I can't tell you

1550
00:59:52,090 --> 00:59:53,240
what it's going to do next,

1551
00:59:53,400 --> 00:59:54,850
but what I will tell

1552
00:59:54,850 --> 00:59:56,300
you is that after one second,

1553
00:59:56,360 --> 00:59:57,700
it will be over here.

1554
00:59:58,280 --> 01:00:00,120
There's only one trajectory

1555
01:00:01,040 --> 01:00:04,160
which goes from here to here in one second.

1556
01:00:04,420 --> 01:00:05,300
There it is.

1557
01:00:05,700 --> 01:00:08,260
If I throw it with the wrong velocity,

1558
01:00:08,460 --> 01:00:09,320
it won't get there.

1559
01:00:10,040 --> 01:00:12,160
So it's just as good to

1560
01:00:12,160 --> 01:00:14,280
know two points along the trajectory

1561
01:00:14,280 --> 01:00:17,020
as to know the two pieces of information

1562
01:00:17,020 --> 01:00:18,880
at a single point along the trajectory.

1563
01:00:18,980 --> 01:00:20,160
Same amount of information.

1564
01:00:20,940 --> 01:00:24,380
Instead of giving the position and velocity at one point,

1565
01:00:24,600 --> 01:00:28,540
I give you the positions at two separate times.

1566
01:00:29,640 --> 01:00:30,980
That's the problem,

1567
01:00:31,220 --> 01:00:35,320
that's another formulation of the question of mechanics.

1568
01:00:35,980 --> 01:00:37,200
Question of mechanics,

1569
01:00:37,580 --> 01:00:40,160
instead of the initial data problem,

1570
01:00:40,440 --> 01:00:43,400
the problem of finding a unique trajectory

1571
01:00:43,640 --> 01:00:45,240
which connects two points.

1572
01:00:47,020 --> 01:00:48,400
In this form,

1573
01:00:49,460 --> 01:00:53,460
the principle of nature that governs trajectories

1574
01:00:53,460 --> 01:00:56,000
is called the principle of least action.

1575
01:00:56,940 --> 01:00:59,540
And what it says is there's some quantity

1576
01:01:00,360 --> 01:01:02,040
associated with this trajectory,

1577
01:01:02,280 --> 01:01:03,420
the whole trajectory,

1578
01:01:03,500 --> 01:01:05,580
not just little pieces of local information,

1579
01:01:05,680 --> 01:01:06,620
but the whole trajectory,

1580
01:01:07,400 --> 01:01:09,200
there's some quantity about that trajectory

1581
01:01:09,200 --> 01:01:13,780
which is minimum for the true trajectory,

1582
01:01:14,060 --> 01:01:15,680
for the true trajectory,

1583
01:01:16,020 --> 01:01:17,600
and will be larger

1584
01:01:18,400 --> 01:01:20,340
for every deviation of the trajectory

1585
01:01:20,340 --> 01:01:21,700
from the true trajectory.

1586
01:01:21,900 --> 01:01:22,840
True trajectory.

1587
01:01:25,500 --> 01:01:26,720
Correct trajectory.

1588
01:01:27,320 --> 01:01:28,480
Here's an example.

1589
01:01:30,140 --> 01:01:31,540
Take two points.

1590
01:01:32,460 --> 01:01:33,580
For simplicity,

1591
01:01:33,580 --> 01:01:35,100
we could take them in two dimensions.

1592
01:01:37,720 --> 01:01:39,600
Calculate the distance between them

1593
01:01:40,640 --> 01:01:42,840
and ask what is the line,

1594
01:01:43,060 --> 01:01:43,340
well,

1595
01:01:43,340 --> 01:01:43,820
not the distance,

1596
01:01:43,940 --> 01:01:45,200
draw a line,

1597
01:01:45,200 --> 01:01:46,600
draw a curve between them.

1598
01:01:52,480 --> 01:01:54,000
Draw any curve between them.

1599
01:01:54,720 --> 01:01:56,400
Calculate the length of that curve

1600
01:01:56,400 --> 01:02:00,760
and then ask what curve minimizes the length.

1601
01:02:01,000 --> 01:02:04,500
What curve gives you the smallest distance

1602
01:02:04,500 --> 01:02:07,140
along the curve between those two points?

1603
01:02:07,620 --> 01:02:08,120
Of course,

1604
01:02:08,120 --> 01:02:08,960
we all know the answer,

1605
01:02:09,020 --> 01:02:09,640
it's a straight line.

1606
01:02:11,100 --> 01:02:13,600
But what's the mathematics that goes into it?

1607
01:02:13,760 --> 01:02:15,680
The mathematics that goes into it

1608
01:02:15,680 --> 01:02:18,200
is minimizing a certain quantity,

1609
01:02:18,380 --> 01:02:20,880
but that quantity is not a function

1610
01:02:20,880 --> 01:02:22,380
of a finite number of variables.

1611
01:02:22,680 --> 01:02:27,080
It's a function of every point along this curve.

1612
01:02:27,560 --> 01:02:31,180
So it's a much more complicated object

1613
01:02:31,180 --> 01:02:33,040
than calculating the minimum

1614
01:02:33,580 --> 01:02:35,260
of a function of a few variables.

1615
01:02:36,640 --> 01:02:38,340
There's two approaches to it.

1616
01:02:38,500 --> 01:02:40,200
One is the local approach,

1617
01:02:40,340 --> 01:02:41,760
which I'll show you what it means in a moment,

1618
01:02:41,920 --> 01:02:43,460
and one is the global approach.

1619
01:02:44,680 --> 01:02:45,200
Yeah,

1620
01:02:45,200 --> 01:02:47,420
let's talk about the local and the global approach.

1621
01:02:48,800 --> 01:02:50,820
The global approach is just what I said.

1622
01:02:50,960 --> 01:02:52,200
You pick your two points,

1623
01:02:53,560 --> 01:02:56,120
you calculate the distance along the curve,

1624
01:02:57,020 --> 01:02:59,840
that's some quantity that depends on the entire curve,

1625
01:03:00,760 --> 01:03:02,820
and then you ask what

1626
01:03:02,820 --> 01:03:04,880
minimizes the length along that curve.

1627
01:03:05,620 --> 01:03:06,580
That's something,

1628
01:03:06,580 --> 01:03:07,780
that's a very global view

1629
01:03:07,780 --> 01:03:09,470
where you minimize something

1630
01:03:09,470 --> 01:03:11,160
associated with the entire curve.

1631
01:03:11,540 --> 01:03:12,060
Now,

1632
01:03:12,060 --> 01:03:13,440
the local point of the curve

1633
01:03:13,460 --> 01:03:14,880
in the view goes as follows.

1634
01:03:15,200 --> 01:03:15,880
All right,

1635
01:03:15,880 --> 01:03:17,200
supposing we know,

1636
01:03:17,280 --> 01:03:17,880
let's focus,

1637
01:03:19,780 --> 01:03:21,880
let's take our little microscope here

1638
01:03:21,880 --> 01:03:23,340
and focus along,

1639
01:03:23,540 --> 01:03:25,440
somewhere along the trajectory over here.

1640
01:03:25,760 --> 01:03:26,620
In fact,

1641
01:03:26,620 --> 01:03:27,380
for our purposes,

1642
01:03:27,420 --> 01:03:29,560
let's imagine breaking up the trajectory

1643
01:03:29,560 --> 01:03:30,900
into a lot of little pieces,

1644
01:03:32,120 --> 01:03:33,840
each of some small length.

1645
01:03:35,600 --> 01:03:37,460
And let's focus right in here.

1646
01:03:39,640 --> 01:03:41,640
The curve comes in over here,

1647
01:03:41,780 --> 01:03:43,380
so it's pinned down over here,

1648
01:03:43,460 --> 01:03:44,900
it goes out over here,

1649
01:03:45,040 --> 01:03:48,300
and I'm interested in where it goes between them.

1650
01:03:48,440 --> 01:03:51,140
Let's just suppose in breaking it up into pieces

1651
01:03:51,140 --> 01:03:52,160
as an approximation.

1652
01:03:52,660 --> 01:03:53,940
As an approximation,

1653
01:03:53,940 --> 01:03:55,840
break up the curve into little pieces,

1654
01:03:56,460 --> 01:04:00,440
and now take two of those little pieces

1655
01:04:00,440 --> 01:04:04,260
and ask where should you locate the midpoint

1656
01:04:05,259 --> 01:04:09,720
in order that the curve be as short as possible.

1657
01:04:10,240 --> 01:04:10,920
Now,

1658
01:04:10,920 --> 01:04:12,240
the answer doesn't depend

1659
01:04:12,240 --> 01:04:14,500
where you put this point

1660
01:04:14,500 --> 01:04:16,980
does not depend on the rest of the curve

1661
01:04:16,980 --> 01:04:20,080
if you happen to know this point and that point.

1662
01:04:22,640 --> 01:04:26,640
If you know the point over here

1663
01:04:27,240 --> 01:04:29,000
and the point over here,

1664
01:04:30,980 --> 01:04:33,380
then the rest of the curve doesn't matter.

1665
01:04:34,480 --> 01:04:35,520
You will have to,

1666
01:04:35,520 --> 01:04:36,760
in any case,

1667
01:04:36,780 --> 01:04:38,140
if you want to make

1668
01:04:38,140 --> 01:04:39,500
the curve as short as possible

1669
01:04:39,500 --> 01:04:42,000
and you know that it passes through here and here,

1670
01:04:42,240 --> 01:04:44,060
then all you have to do is ask

1671
01:04:44,060 --> 01:04:46,240
how do you make that little segment between them

1672
01:04:46,240 --> 01:04:47,300
as short as possible.

1673
01:04:48,060 --> 01:04:49,040
What's the answer?

1674
01:04:49,820 --> 01:04:51,140
The answer is obvious,

1675
01:04:51,960 --> 01:04:54,600
but it's a local version of the same question.

1676
01:04:54,820 --> 01:04:57,500
It just depends on this little region over here.

1677
01:04:57,700 --> 01:04:59,020
The answer is obvious.

1678
01:04:59,400 --> 01:05:00,580
Just go straight ahead.

1679
01:05:00,780 --> 01:05:04,180
Move this point until this little piece of the curve

1680
01:05:04,180 --> 01:05:05,260
